<assessment id="u4_m2_testprop4_tutor2">
    <title>Tutor</title>

<page>
    <content>
        <p>If we take a different random sample and get a test statistic of zero, what can we
            conclude? Mark each statement as true or false.</p>
    </content>
    <question id="q1">
        <body>1) p-hat = p<sub>o</sub>:</body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">true</choice>
            <choice value="B">false</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
                <response match="A" name="true" score="10">
                    <feedback>Correct. When p-hat = p<sub>o</sub>, we get z = 0 /
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221845-0500"?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221916-0500" comment="change correct?"?>standard
                        deviation<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221843-0500" content="s.d."?>
                        = 0.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response match="B" name="false">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. When p-hat = p<sub>o</sub>, we get z = 0 /
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221856-0500"?>standard
                        deviation<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221854-0500" content="s.d."?><?oxy_comment_end?>
                        = 0.</feedback>
                </response>
            </part>
    </question>
    <question id="q2">
        <body>2)
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222040-0500"?>T<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222039-0500" content="t"?>he
                proportion for this sample is equal to
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T221930-0500"?>the
                <?oxy_insert_end?>hypothesized value for the proportion in the population: </body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">true</choice>
            <choice value="B">false</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A" name="true" score="10">
                <feedback>Correct.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B" name="false">
                <feedback>Incorrect. This statement in symbols is p-hat =
                    p<sub>o</sub>.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
    <question id="q3">
        <body>3) p-hat is 0 standard deviations away from p<sub>o</sub>:</body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">true</choice>
            <choice value="B">false</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A" name="true" score="10">
                <feedback>Correct.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B" name="false">
                <feedback>Incorrect. The test statistic z measures how many standard
                    deviations p-hat is from p<sub>o</sub>.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
    <question id="q4">
        <body>4<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222021-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222021-0500" content=":"?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222056-0500"?>T<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222055-0500" content="t"?>he
                standard deviation is 0: </body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">true</choice>
            <choice value="B">false</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A" name="true">
                <feedback>Incorrect. If the standard deviation is 0, then there is no
                        variability in sample proportions. p-hat = p<sub>o</sub> for
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222112-0500"?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222128-0500" comment="use italic for emphasis"?>every<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222115-0500" content="EVERY"?>
                        sample. In this strange situation we would not need to do a hypothesis
                        test<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222137-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        because we would already know the value of p<sub>o</sub>.
                        Also<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222153-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        the test statistic is not defined when the denominator is 0. </feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B" name="false" score="10">
                <feedback>Correct. If the standard deviation is 0, then there is no variability in
                        sample proportions. p-hat = p<sub>o</sub> for
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222214-0500"?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222236-0500" comment="use italic for emphasis"?>every<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222216-0500" content="EVERY"?>
                        sample. In this strange situation we would not need to do a hypothesis
                        test<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T222248-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        because we would already know the value of p<sub>o</sub>. Also the test
                        statistic is not defined when the denominator is 0.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
</page>
</assessment>
